"""
MKT Context — 1 Kings chapters 3–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-3-5-full.py

Ch3: Solomon's treaty marriage; Gibeon incubation dream; wisdom request; divided-child judgment (28 verses)
Ch4: Administrative officials; 12-district system; provisions; Solomonic wisdom lists (34 verses)
Ch5: Hiram alliance; Lebanon cedar trade; corvée labor force; temple quarrying (18 verses)

Context focus: ANE diplomatic marriage practice, incubation dreams, Egyptian/Mesopotamian
wisdom traditions, Phoenician trade networks, corvée labor archaeology, onomastica lists.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The marriage alliance (<em>ḥitten</em>) with Pharaoh king of Egypt was a standard instrument of ANE diplomacy: a subordinate or equal power cemented a political relationship by receiving a royal daughter. What is remarkable here is the direction — it was almost unheard of for an Egyptian pharaoh to give a daughter in marriage to a foreign king; Egyptian daughters were given to Egyptian men. The Amarna letters show that Near Eastern kings repeatedly requested Egyptian princesses and were refused. Solomon&#8217;s receipt of Pharaoh&#8217;s daughter thus signals Egypt&#8217;s acknowledgment of his international standing. The pharaoh is usually identified as one of the late Twenty-First Dynasty kings (Siamun or Psusennes II, ca. 978&#8211;943 BCE); the marriage probably occurred early in Solomon&#8217;s reign. Her temporary lodging &#8220;in the city of David&#8221; indicates the palace complex was not yet built — the temple and palace took 20 years (6:38; 7:1). This verse opens the Solomon narrative&#8217;s complex ambiguity: the greatest king in Israel&#8217;s history begins with an act that Deuteronomy 17:17 will later classify as royal violation (&#8220;he shall not acquire many wives for himself&#8221;).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The qualification about high places (<em>bāmôt</em>) is the Deuteronomistic historian&#8217;s standard framework for evaluating pre-temple worship. <em>Bāmôt</em> (sing. <em>bāmāh</em>) were open-air cultic platforms, often on hills, widely attested archaeologically throughout Canaan and used for sacrifice, votive offerings, and cultic meals. The Gezer, Megiddo, and Dan excavations have all uncovered bāmôt remains. The historian acknowledges a transitional legitimacy: &#8220;no house had yet been built for the name of YHWH&#8221; — before the temple, decentralized worship at high places was understandable, if not ideal. After the temple&#8217;s completion, sacrifice anywhere but Jerusalem becomes the cardinal sin catalogued in the evaluation of every subsequent king. This verse thus establishes the benchmark against which all future Israelite and Judahite kings will be measured: the temple-centralization ideal of Deuteronomy 12.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s characterization as one who &#8220;loved YHWH and walked in the statutes of David his father&#8221; is the highest praise the Deuteronomistic historian can give, using the covenant-loyalty vocabulary of Deuteronomy (&#8220;love YHWH your God,&#8221; Deut 6:5). The exception &#8220;except that he offered sacrifice at the high places&#8221; is the narrator&#8217;s literary preparation for the Gibeon scene: Solomon&#8217;s virtue and his cultic ambiguity are held in tension from the outset. The Deuteronomistic history evaluates kings not primarily by military success or economic achievement but by covenant fidelity — Solomon&#8217;s greatness and his eventual failure are both framed in these terms.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Gibeon was &#8220;the great high place&#8221; (<em>habāmāh haggĕdôlāh</em>) — its status is explained by 2 Chronicles 1:3&#8211;6, which specifies that the tabernacle of Moses (the tent of meeting) and the bronze altar were located at Gibeon at this time. The ark was in Jerusalem (2 Sam 6), but the wilderness tabernacle and its altar were at Gibeon — so Gibeon was the most legitimate worship site outside Jerusalem. Solomon&#8217;s 1,000 burnt offerings (<em>ʿôlôt</em>) were an extraordinary royal sacrifice demonstrating piety on a scale appropriate to the king&#8217;s status. Comparable royal mega-sacrifice is attested in Ugaritic and Hittite royal texts where kings offer hundreds of animals before major undertakings or during national crises. The <em>ʿôlāh</em> (whole burnt offering, entirely consumed) was the most expensive and complete form of sacrifice: nothing was returned to the worshiper.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The incubation dream (<em>ḥălôm hallaylāh</em>, &#8220;dream of the night&#8221;) was a recognized ANE religious practice: the petitioner would sleep at a sacred site, having prepared through ritual purification and sacrifice, in order to receive divine communication in a dream. Incubation dreams are well documented in Mesopotamian and Egyptian sources — the Sphinx Dream Stele of Thutmose IV describes an incubation dream at Giza where the sphinx-god promises him the kingship if he clears the sand. Hittite royal rituals include incubation procedures for receiving oracles. The form of the exchange — YHWH appears, offers &#8220;ask what I shall give you,&#8221; the petitioner responds, YHWH grants — follows the ANE treaty-grant pattern: the suzerain offers the vassal a gift, the vassal articulates the desired benefit, the suzerain grants with conditions. The setting at Gibeon contextualizes the dream: it occurs at the legitimate cultic site after maximal sacrifice.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s invocation of David&#8217;s covenant faithfulness (<em>ḥesed</em>) as the basis for his petition follows the standard ANE suzerain-vassal prayer pattern: the petitioner recalls past benefactions as grounds for present request. The term <em>ḥesed</em> (steadfast love, covenant loyalty) is the relational term describing YHWH&#8217;s commitment to his covenant partner — it is not mere sentiment but binding treaty obligation. David&#8217;s <em>ʾĕmet</em> (faithfulness/integrity) and <em>yāšār lĕbāb</em> (uprightness of heart) are the covenant qualities the narrator uses to distinguish David from Saul. Solomon presents himself as the beneficiary of David&#8217;s covenant standing — a relational inheritance that is standard in ANE dynastic logic: the son inherits the father&#8217;s treaty relationship with the suzerain.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s self-description as &#8220;a little child&#8221; (<em>naʿar qāṭôn</em>) who &#8220;does not know how to go out or come in&#8221; employs the conventional royal humility formula attested in ANE correspondence. In the Amarna letters, vassal kings regularly describe themselves as &#8220;the dirt at the feet of my lord&#8221; and as ignorant and inexperienced — formulaic self-abasement before the superior party is the expected posture in treaty contexts. The expression &#8220;go out and come in&#8221; (<em>lāṣēt wālābôʾ</em>) is an idiom for military leadership and administrative governance (Num 27:17; Deut 31:2; 1 Sam 18:16) — Solomon acknowledges inexperience precisely in the domain where a king is most needed: warfare and judgment.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s description of Israel as &#8220;a great people, too numerous to be counted or numbered for multitude&#8221; echoes YHWH&#8217;s promises to Abraham (Gen 15:5; 22:17; 32:12 — &#8220;as numerous as the stars&#8221;/&#8220;as the sand of the sea&#8221;) and Moses (Deut 1:10; 10:22). This is the narrator&#8217;s signal that the Solomonic era represents the fulfillment of the patriarchal promise: the nation has become &#8220;great.&#8221; The context for the wisdom request is thus explicitly covenantal: Solomon needs wisdom to govern the people YHWH promised Abraham, not merely administrative competence to run a state bureaucracy.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Lēb šōmēaʿ</em> — &#8220;a hearing/listening heart&#8221; — is the MKT&#8217;s &#8220;understanding mind,&#8221; but the Hebrew is more bodily and more receptive than &#8220;understanding.&#8221; In Hebrew anthropology the <em>lēb</em> (heart) is the center of thought, will, and discernment, not primarily emotion. A &#8220;hearing heart&#8221; is one that listens before it speaks, discerns before it decides — the ideal judicial quality. In the Egyptian wisdom tradition, the pharaoh&#8217;s wisdom to judge was considered a divine gift: the Instruction of Ptahhotep describes the ideal official as one whose &#8220;heart is a balance&#8221; — weighing cases without partiality. The verb <em>šāmaʿ</em> (hear) is the same root as in the Shema (Deut 6:4): covenant hearing is not merely acoustic but obedient reception of the divine word. Solomon requests the capacity to hear YHWH&#8217;s mind in order to govern YHWH&#8217;s people.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The narrator&#8217;s brief notation that YHWH was pleased (<em>wayyîṭab haddābār</em>) follows the conventional ANE treaty-grant pattern: the suzerain approves the vassal&#8217;s request as appropriate. Solomon&#8217;s petition is theologically evaluated as correct: he asked for a governance gift rather than personal goods (long life, riches, military victory — the three standard wishes of ANE royal petitions are noted explicitly in v.11 as what Solomon did not request). The theological evaluation is explicit: wisdom-for-governance is the appropriate royal request.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH&#8217;s response lists the three things Solomon did not ask for — long life (<em>ʾārakîm yāmîm</em>), riches (<em>ʿōšer</em>), and the death of enemies (<em>nepeš ʾōyĕbêkā</em>) — as the typical self-serving requests a king might make. The ANE royal inscription genre is filled with prayers for exactly these: &#8220;grant me long life, abundant riches, and victory over all enemies.&#8221; Solomon&#8217;s wisdom in asking for wisdom (rather than for the goods wisdom produces) is itself wisdom. YHWH praises the request as demonstrating the very quality asked for: a ruler who knows that governance of others requires discernment will ask for discernment rather than personal benefit.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH&#8217;s grant of &#8220;a wise and discerning heart (<em>lēb ḥākām wĕnābôn</em>)&#8221; — unprecedented before or after Solomon — is the theological warrant for the rest of the Solomonic narrative. The paired terms <em>ḥākām</em> (wise, skilled) and <em>nābôn</em> (discerning, perceptive) appear together in the Joseph narrative (Gen 41:33,39) where Pharaoh recognizes that YHWH has given Joseph exactly this quality. The claim that &#8220;no one like you has been before you and no one like you shall arise after you&#8221; is a royal hyperbole common in ANE royal inscriptions (the Ramesses II Kadesh poem uses similar language) but is also the theological foundation for the Solomonic wisdom tradition and the literary corpus attributed to him (Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Songs, Wisdom of Solomon).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The unsolicited gifts of riches (<em>ʿōšer</em>) and honor (<em>kābôd</em>) follow ANE treaty-grant logic: the suzerain who grants the vassal&#8217;s request also adds unrequested benefits to demonstrate generosity. The formulation &#8220;so that no other king shall compare with you all your days&#8221; is the hyperbolic royal comparison formula standard in ANE royal ideology — the king is always declared superior to all contemporaries and predecessors. In the theological framework of Kings, however, the accumulation of wealth and honor is double-edged: it is the sign of YHWH&#8217;s blessing but also the material for the covenant violations catalogued in Deuteronomy 17 (horses from Egypt, many wives, accumulation of silver and gold).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The conditional attached to the unconditional gifts (&#8220;if you walk in my ways and keep my statutes and commandments as David your father walked&#8221;) is the Deuteronomistic covenant condition. The grant of wisdom, wealth, and honor is unconditional; long life is conditional. This follows the ANE distinction between unconditional royal grant (permanent) and conditional covenant (requiring ongoing obedience). The Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7) is similarly structured: the dynasty is promised unconditionally but individual kings&#8217; reigns are conditioned on obedience. Solomon&#8217;s failure to keep this condition (ch11: foreign wives, high places, idols) will explain the division of the kingdom — YHWH kept his promise by leaving one tribe for David&#8217;s sake.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s awakening to find it &#8220;a dream&#8221; does not diminish the revelation — in ANE understanding, incubation dreams were authoritative divine communication. The celebration at Jerusalem &#8220;before the ark of the covenant&#8221; with burnt offerings (<em>ʿôlôt</em>), peace offerings (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>), and a feast for his servants follows the appropriate response pattern: the beneficiary of a divine grant acknowledges it publicly with sacrifice and communal celebration. The ark in Jerusalem is the legitimate cultic object associated with YHWH&#8217;s presence (2 Sam 6; 1 Kgs 8); the return to Jerusalem from Gibeon with feast and sacrifice marks the integration of the Gibeon revelation into the Zion-centered cult.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The transition from the royal dream oracle to the judgment scene is abrupt but narratively purposeful: the Gibeon dream granted wisdom; the scene of the two prostitutes demonstrates that wisdom in action. The social setting is deliberate — two women who are prostitutes (<em>zōnôt</em>) represent those at the margins of Israelite society with no male advocate and no social standing to press claims. The king as supreme judge accessible to the lowest social class is an ANE royal ideal: the prologue to the Code of Hammurabi describes Hammurabi as a shepherd who protects the widow and orphan; Egyptian wisdom texts (Instruction of Amenemhet) describe the just king as one who hears the case of the poor. The test of Solomon&#8217;s wisdom comes precisely from those whose cases the administrative system is least equipped to adjudicate — their dispute has no witnesses, no documentary evidence, only competing testimony.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The narrative structure of the women&#8217;s testimony follows the legal convention of first person direct speech before a judge: each woman presents her case, addresses the king directly, and invokes the material facts. The two women share a house — they are of the same economic and social class. The birth setting &#8220;in the house, alone&#8221; (v.18) means there are no witnesses to the identity of the live child — the classic &#8220;witness-free&#8221; case where the judge cannot rely on external evidence. The legal question is pure: which woman&#8217;s testimony is to be believed when no corroborating evidence exists?</p>",
    "18": "<p>The detail that the two births occurred &#8220;three days apart&#8221; and that they were &#8220;alone in the house&#8221; (&#8220;no stranger with us in the house&#8221;) is the narrator&#8217;s establishment of the evidentiary impasse: there are no third-party witnesses. The house shared by two unmarried women with infants of different fathers is the social reality of ancient Near Eastern urban poverty. The lack of witnesses is the legal crux — the entire force of the king&#8217;s judgment depends on the impossibility of adjudicating the case by conventional evidence.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The accusation of &#8220;overlaying&#8221; (<em>šākab ʿal</em>) — accidentally crushing the infant by rolling onto it during sleep — is the &#8220;natural death&#8221; explanation offered as the alternative to the accusation of child-swapping. Infant mortality through overlaying was recognized in ancient law codes: the Middle Assyrian Laws address cases of infant death by overlaying. The woman&#8217;s attribution of the infant&#8217;s death to overlaying rather than to deliberate harm is the plausible excuse — which may be true (her own child died) or may be the alibi for the substitution.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The alleged substitution narrative — &#8220;she rose at midnight, took my son from my side, laid her dead son at my breast&#8221; — describes a specific act of deception: the sleeping woman is presented as the victim of a calculated exchange. The detail &#8220;while your servant slept&#8221; explains the evidentiary gap. The midnight setting recalls the Passover (Exod 12:29, YHWH struck Egypt&#8217;s firstborn &#8220;at midnight&#8221;) — a literary resonance that is probably not accidental; dead children and royal verdicts about life and death are the shared context.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The discovery &#8220;in the morning when I rose to nurse my child, behold, he was dead. But when I looked at him carefully in the morning, behold, it was not the child I had borne&#8221; — the maternal identification by close inspection &#8220;in the morning light&#8221; is the empirical claim that depends on the mother&#8217;s knowledge of her own child&#8217;s body. In ANE legal context, maternal recognition was considered a legitimate form of identification: the Nippur marriage contracts and adoption documents describe mothers&#8217; rights in terms of intimate knowledge of the child. The dispute thus turns on whose claim to personal knowledge is credible.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The counter-claim and the alternating insistence (&#8220;No, the living one is mine and the dead one is yours; no, the dead one is yours and the living one is mine&#8221;) is the stalemate that no conventional legal procedure can resolve. The rapid back-and-forth exchange in vv. 22&#8211;23 is the narrator&#8217;s dramatization of the evidentiary impasse before Solomon — this case cannot be decided by witnesses, documents, or oaths; it requires a different form of adjudication entirely.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s restatement of the dispute &#8220;in your own words&#8221; is the judicial technique of summarizing the claims before judgment — attested in Mesopotamian legal documents where the judge (<em>dayy&#257;num</em>) rehearses the parties&#8217; positions before rendering a verdict. The restatement confirms that the king has heard both sides accurately, a requirement of just judgment in ANE legal tradition (Hammurabi&#8217;s Code prologue: &#8220;I established law and justice&#8221;). The narrative tension is at its peak: no evidence, no witnesses, only competing assertions.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The command &#8220;bring me a sword&#8221; is Solomon&#8217;s famous judicial innovation — not a verdict but a test. The sword as symbol of royal justice and power is standard in ANE royal iconography: Egyptian pharaohs are depicted wielding the <em>khepesh</em> (scimitar) in judicial and military contexts; Mesopotamian king figures hold maces or swords as symbols of justice. Solomon&#8217;s &#8220;sword command&#8221; is not a threat but a technique: the proposed action will force a behavioral response that is more revealing than any testimony.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The command &#8220;divide the living child in two, and give half to one and half to the other&#8221; is the test. ANE and Indian wisdom literature contain parallel &#8220;divided-baby&#8221; or &#8220;divided-object&#8221; judgment stories — the closest parallel is in the Buddhist Jataka tales and in Indian law literature, where a judge uses the same technique. The widespread occurrence of the motif across cultures suggests it represents a cross-cultural wisdom ideal: the judge who devises a test that reveals truth through behavior rather than evidence. Whether historical or exemplary narrative, the story demonstrates wisdom at work: Solomon&#8217;s insight is that the true mother will surrender her rights rather than see the child destroyed.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The true mother&#8217;s response &#8220;her heart yearned for her son&#8221; (<em>nikmĕrû raḥamêhā ʿal bĕnāh</em>) employs the term <em>raḥamîm</em> (compassion/womb-love, from <em>reḥem</em>, womb) — the same word used for YHWH&#8217;s compassion toward Israel (Isa 49:15: &#8220;can a woman forget her nursing child, that she should have no compassion for the son of her womb?&#8221;). The mother&#8217;s willingness to give up her legal claim (&#8220;give her the living child — only do not kill him&#8221;) is the behavioral test result: a false claimant would accept the division as partial victory; only the true mother would surrender all rights to preserve the child&#8217;s life. The false mother&#8217;s response (&#8220;it shall be neither mine nor yours — divide it&#8221;) reveals her motive: she wants to neutralize the rival&#8217;s advantage, not to care for the child.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s verdict &#8220;give the first woman the living child; she is his mother&#8221; is the judicial application of behavioral evidence: the king read the women&#8217;s emotional responses as data that conventional testimony could not provide. ANE judicial theory did not exclude psychological and behavioral evidence — Mesopotamian judges could examine demeanor, take oaths at the temple, or require ordeal (river ordeal) to supplement testimonial evidence. Solomon&#8217;s technique is more elegant: he creates conditions under which truth reveals itself through action. The verdict requires no witnesses and no oath — the behavioral test has supplied what evidence could not.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The response of &#8220;all Israel&#8221; — that they feared (<em>wayyirʾû</em>) the king and saw that &#8220;divine wisdom was in him to do justice (<em>mišpāṭ</em>)&#8221; — is the political conclusion the narrative drives toward: the king&#8217;s divinely-given wisdom has been publicly demonstrated in the most difficult possible case. The fear of the king is not terror but the awe-response to wisdom that is recognized as more than human (the same root used for the &#8220;fear of YHWH&#8221; in the wisdom tradition). The phrase &#8220;wisdom of God was in him&#8221; (<em>ḥokmat &#8217;ĕlōhîm bĕqirbô</em>) echoes Pharaoh&#8217;s recognition of Joseph: &#8220;can we find a man like this, in whom is the Spirit of God?&#8221; (Gen 41:38). The narrative establishes that Solomon&#8217;s wisdom is not merely intelligence but a divine endowment publicly verified.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>&#8220;King Solomon was king over all Israel&#8221; — the tautological introduction (&#8220;king Solomon was king&#8221;) is the Deuteronomistic historian&#8217;s standard opening for a reign summary. &#8220;All Israel&#8221; (<em>kol yiśrāʾēl</em>) is significant: the united monarchy under David and Solomon is the theological ideal against which the divided kingdom will always be measured as deficient. Chapter 4 is an administrative document — a list of officials and district governors — that demonstrates the institutional reality of Solomonic imperial governance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The list of chief officials (<em>śārîm</em>) in vv. 2&#8211;6 mirrors Egyptian and Canaanite court organization. The position of &#8220;priest&#8221; at the head of the list is unusual (priests normally follow military commanders) but reflects the theocratic ideal of the Solomonic court: the priest is first because the state exists under YHWH&#8217;s sovereign ordering. Azariah son of Zadok as priest continues the Zadokite line that will be decisive in Ezekiel&#8217;s ideal temple (Ezek 40&#8211;48) and in post-exilic priestly genealogy.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The two &#8220;secretaries&#8221; (<em>sōpĕrîm</em>) and the &#8220;recorder&#8221; (<em>mazkîr</em>) are offices modeled on Egyptian court bureaucracy. The <em>sōpēr</em> (scribe/secretary) was the keeper of royal correspondence, legal documents, and state records — equivalent to the Egyptian royal scribe (<em>sš nsw</em>). The <em>mazkîr</em> (herald/recorder) was responsible for announcing royal decisions and maintaining the official chronicle — the Egyptian equivalent was the court herald (<em>whm.w</em>). These offices indicate that Solomon&#8217;s court had adopted the administrative apparatus of the great empire states.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Benaiah son of Jehoiada&#8217;s appointment &#8220;over the army&#8221; reflects the continuity from David&#8217;s court (2 Sam 23:20&#8211;23) where Benaiah was chief of the Cherethites and Pelethites (the royal guard). His elevation to supreme military command rewards his loyalty to Solomon against Adonijah and Joab (1 Kgs 2:25,34). The dual listing of &#8220;Zadok and Abiathar as priests&#8221; reflects the editorial confusion of an earlier source: Abiathar was exiled in 1 Kgs 2:27, so this list may derive from an earlier administrative document preserved intact.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The offices &#8220;over the district officers&#8221; (Azariah son of Nathan, who supervised the 12 governors of v.7) and &#8220;priest and king&#8217;s friend&#8221; (<em>rēaʿ hammelek</em>) are known from Egyptian administrative organization — the &#8220;friend of the king&#8221; was a specific court title in Egypt designating a senior advisor or companion of the pharaoh. The title <em>rēaʿ hammelek</em> also appears in 2 Samuel 15:37 and 16:16 for Hushai. The presence of Nathan&#8217;s sons in key administrative positions reflects the reward structure for prophetic loyalty: Nathan&#8217;s support for Solomon in 1 Kings 1 secured his family&#8217;s position.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The office &#8220;over the forced labor&#8221; (<em>ʿal hammās</em>) held by Adoniram son of Abda is the most consequential in the list for later narrative. The <em>mas</em> (forced labor, corvée) was the mechanism by which Solomon built his empire — the temple, palace, store cities, and fortifications all required massive organized labor. Adoniram supervised this system and will be the figure stoned to death when Rehoboam sends him to the northern tribes in 12:18, triggering the schism. His presence here establishes the institutional machinery that will later become the instrument of oppression.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The 12-district system for supplying the palace is one of the most significant administrative innovations in Israelite history. The districts do not follow tribal boundaries (compare the tribal allotments of Joshua 13&#8211;19) but are organized for economic efficiency — their boundaries reflect agricultural zones, trade routes, and population distribution rather than ancestral tribal territories. The system required each district to supply the palace for one month per year — an enormous logistical achievement that presupposes a sophisticated bureaucratic infrastructure with written records, standardized measures, and supervisory hierarchies. The rotation system also distributes the burden evenly across the kingdom.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;Ben-hur, in the hill country of Ephraim&#8221; — the use of &#8220;Ben-&#8221; (son of) names without patronyms for several governors may indicate that these were younger officials whose fathers were not yet notable, or that the source document used abbreviated forms. The hill country of Ephraim was one of the most agriculturally productive regions of the central highlands, with terraced agriculture producing grain, olives, and grapes. The district corresponds roughly to the tribal territory of Ephraim in Joshua&#8217;s allotments.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ben-deker&#8217;s district in &#8220;Makaz, Shaalbim, Beth-shemesh, and Elon-beth-hanan&#8221; covers the western foothills (Shephelah) between the Judean highlands and the coastal plain — a strategic area controlling access routes to Jerusalem. Beth-shemesh is archaeologically well-attested and was an important border town; Shaalbim is listed in Judges 1:35 as not yet conquered from the Amorites. The inclusion of these territories indicates that under Solomon the formerly Canaanite western Shephelah was fully integrated into the administrative system.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ben-hesed&#8217;s territory of Arubboth &#8220;with Socoh and all the land of Hepher&#8221; covers the western slopes of the Carmel range and the Sharon plain. Socoh appears in Joshua&#8217;s tribal allotments (Josh 15:48 for a Judean Socoh; Josh 16:6 context). The &#8220;land of Hepher&#8221; is associated with the daughters of Zelophehad (Num 26:33; Josh 17:3) — its inclusion here shows the administrative rationalization of what were historically distinct territorial claims.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ben-abinadab in &#8220;all Naphath-dor&#8221; (the coastal region around Dor) — the detail that he &#8220;had Solomon&#8217;s daughter Taphath as his wife&#8221; is a note about the royal marriage policy: Solomon used daughters as instruments of political alliance with district governors, paralleling the international marriage diplomacy (Pharaoh&#8217;s daughter, ch3:1) at the domestic level. Dor was a Canaanite port city on the Mediterranean coast north of Caesarea, important for maritime trade; its integration into the Solomonic administrative system reflects the absorption of Canaanite coastal territory.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Baana son of Ahilud&#8217;s territory covers the Jezreel Valley and Beth-shean region — among the most strategically important land in Canaan, controlling the main trade and military route between the Jordan valley and the coastal plain. Megiddo (Tel Megiddo, archaeologically excavated) was one of Solomon&#8217;s major chariot cities (9:15); the Solomonic stables at Megiddo were excavated by the Oriental Institute expedition (Lamon and Shipton, 1939), though the attribution of these stables to Solomon or Ahab remains debated. The Jezreel Valley&#8217;s agricultural productivity made this district one of the most valuable in the kingdom.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Ben-geber&#8217;s territory in Ramoth-gilead (Transjordan) includes the villages of Jair son of Manasseh and the region of Argob in Bashan (&#8220;sixty great cities with walls and bronze bars&#8221;) — the largest territorial unit in the list. Argob/Bashan was the territory of the giant king Og (Deut 3:1&#8211;13; Num 21:33&#8211;35), whose defeat was one of the foundational conquest narratives. The inclusion of this large Transjordanian territory shows that Solomon&#8217;s administrative reach extended beyond the Jordan — the Transjordanian tribes (Reuben, Gad, half-Manasseh) were integrated into the district system.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahinadab son of Iddo &#8220;in Mahanaim&#8221; — Mahanaim (&#8220;two camps&#8221;) was the site of Jacob&#8217;s encounter with the divine messengers (Gen 32:2) and the temporary capital of Ish-bosheth&#8217;s rival court (2 Sam 2:8) before David&#8217;s consolidation. Its assignment as a district center under Solomon represents the administrative incorporation of the former Saulide political center into the Solomonic system — the symbolic geography is deliberate: even the rival house&#8217;s capital is now a provincial town.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ahimaaz &#8220;in Naphtali&#8221; is noted as having &#8220;Basemath, Solomon&#8217;s daughter, as his wife&#8221; — a second instance of Solomon&#8217;s daughters being used to bind district governors to the royal house through marriage. Naphtali in the far north was a frontier territory bordering Aram (Syria); securing it through a royal marriage alliance with the governor was politically prudent. Ahimaaz son of Zadok (2 Sam 15:27; 17:17&#8211;20) was a famous runner in the David narratives; if this is the same person, the district assignment would be a reward for loyalty.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Baanah son of Hushai in &#8220;Asher and Bealoth&#8221; — the coastal territory of Asher in the western Galilee, including the Phoenician borderlands. Hushai was David&#8217;s &#8220;friend/advisor&#8221; who foiled Ahithophel&#8217;s counsel (2 Sam 15:32&#8211;37; 16:16&#8211;19); his son&#8217;s governorship of the northern coastal district rewards the family&#8217;s loyalty. Asher&#8217;s territory bordered Phoenician Tyre — the district governor here would have been involved in the Hiram negotiations of chapter 5.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jehoshaphat son of Paruah &#8220;in Issachar&#8221; — the Jezreel Valley&#8217;s southern edge and the lower Galilee hills. Issachar was known for agricultural productivity (Gen 49:14&#8211;15: &#8220;Issachar is a strong donkey ... he saw that a resting place was good ... and bowed his shoulder to bear burdens&#8221;) — the tribal territory provided abundant provisions for the district system. The district boundaries here seem to align more closely with tribal territory than the earlier districts, possibly reflecting different source documents behind the list.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Shimei son of Ela &#8220;in Benjamin&#8221; — Benjamin&#8217;s assignment as a single district (the only tribe named directly in the list) reflects its small size and its political sensitivity: Benjamin was Saul&#8217;s tribe, and the integration of Benjaminite territory into Solomon&#8217;s administrative system is the final assimilation of the formerly rival tribal heartland. The Shimei of 1 Kgs 2:36&#8211;46 (whose execution Solomon commanded) was a Benjaminite; whether this Shimei is related is unknown.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Geber son of Uri &#8220;in the land of Gilead, the territory of Sihon king of the Amorites and Og king of Bashan&#8221; — note the overlap with Ben-geber&#8217;s territory in v. 13. The LXX resolves the apparent duplication differently. The repeated identification of this region by its pre-conquest occupants (Sihon and Og) is the Deuteronomistic historian&#8217;s convention for the Transjordanian territory — it anchors the Solomonic administrative district in the conquest narrative (Num 21:21&#8211;35; Deut 2:26&#8211;3:17). The final note &#8220;one official who was over all the land&#8221; may indicate a super-governor overseeing multiple Transjordanian districts.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;Judah and Israel were as numerous as the sand by the sea; they ate and drank and were happy&#8221; — the fulfillment of the Abrahamic blessing (Gen 22:17; 32:12) is the theological center of the summary description of Solomon&#8217;s reign. The threefold description — eating, drinking, being happy (<em>śāmēaḥ</em>) — echoes the covenant blessing formula of Deuteronomy (&#8220;you shall eat and be full and bless YHWH&#8221;; Deut 8:10; 12:7,12,18; 14:26). Deuteronomy&#8217;s vision of covenant blessing is agricultural abundance and communal joy; the Solomonic era represents the maximal fulfillment of this ideal in Israel&#8217;s history before the exile.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s dominion &#8220;from the Euphrates to the land of the Philistines and the border of Egypt&#8221; represents the ideal boundaries of the Abrahamic grant (Gen 15:18: &#8220;from the river of Egypt to the great river Euphrates&#8221;) — this is the one moment in biblical history when Israel&#8217;s territorial reach approaches the patriarchal promise. The phrase &#8220;brought tribute (<em>minḥāh</em>) and served Solomon all the days of his life&#8221; reflects the ANE imperial system of vassal tribute: client states acknowledged suzerainty by annual payment of silver, gold, and luxury goods. The Amarna letters document a similar system of tributary relationships in the Late Bronze Age.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s &#8220;daily provision&#8221; (<em>leḥem Šĕlōmōh lĕyôm ʾeḥāḏ</em>) of thirty cors of fine flour, sixty cors of ordinary flour (one cor ≈ 220&#8211;230 liters) represents enormous quantities: approximately 6,600&#8211;7,000 liters of flour per day for fine and ordinary grades respectively. These quantities fed the court, officials, guards, and their households. Comparative ANE data: the Neo-Assyrian palace ration lists (from Nimrud and Nineveh) document similarly large provisions for the royal court; the Ugaritic palace archives record grain and oil rations at a comparable scale. The detail establishes the logistical scale of the Solomonic court as genuinely imperial.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The meat provisions — ten fat oxen, twenty pasture-fed cattle, a hundred sheep, plus deer, gazelles, roebucks, and fatted fowl — demonstrate a court cuisine that included both domestic livestock and wild game. The wild game list (deer/hart, gazelle, roebuck, and fattened fowl) is significant: hunting was a royal activity in ANE culture, and the provision of game for the royal table was part of the administration of royal forests and game reserves. Mesopotamian and Persian royal hunts were elaborate state activities; the inclusion of wild game alongside domestic animals marks Solomon&#8217;s table as genuinely royal rather than merely administrative.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The geographic description &#8220;west of the Euphrates, from Tiphsah to Gaza&#8221; — Tiphsah is probably Thapsacus on the upper Euphrates, the ford marking the northern boundary; Gaza is the southern coastal city marking the Philistine border. This sweeps the entire Levantine corridor from the Euphrates to the Egyptian border — the maximum extent of the Solomonic empire in its vassal-tribute form. The phrase &#8220;he had peace on all sides round about him&#8221; (<em>šālôm mikkol &#8217;ĕbāḏāyw</em>) echoes the Davidic promise of rest from enemies (2 Sam 7:9&#8211;11) and anticipates the temple-building condition: &#8220;rest on every side&#8221; (5:4).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;Each man under his own vine and under his own fig tree, from Dan to Beersheba, all the days of Solomon&#8221; — this is the classic OT formula for peace and agricultural prosperity: vine and fig tree as symbols of settled, owned, productive land (Mic 4:4; Zech 3:10). The idiom &#8220;from Dan to Beersheba&#8221; (the northernmost to southernmost points) marks the national territory. The verse is the Deuteronomistic historian&#8217;s summary verdict on Solomon&#8217;s golden age: the covenant ideal of Deuteronomy&#8217;s blessing section (Deut 28:1&#8211;14) was briefly achieved. The Micah 4:4 echo links this moment to the eschatological vision of restored peace — Solomon&#8217;s era anticipates the messianic kingdom.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Forty thousand stalls for chariot horses and twelve thousand horsemen — this is the verse most directly in tension with Deuteronomy 17:16 (&#8220;he must not acquire many horses for himself or cause the people to return to Egypt in order to acquire many horses, since YHWH has said to you, &#8216;you shall never return that way again&#8217;&#8221;). The parallel in 2 Chronicles 9:25 gives 4,000 stalls — either a scribal corruption or a harmonization with Deuteronomy&#8217;s prohibition. The archaeological evidence: Megiddo stratum IVA (Ahab period, 9th century) shows extensive stable complexes; the attribution to Solomon remains debated. Regardless, the narrator&#8217;s inclusion of this massive cavalry force is editorially significant — Solomon&#8217;s glory is simultaneously sowing the seeds of covenant violation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The district governors&#8217; faithful supply of provisions — &#8220;each in his month&#8221; — fulfilled their primary administrative function: feeding the king&#8217;s table and the royal household. The verb <em>kālkĕlû</em> (supplied/sustained, from <em>kûl</em>) is the same root used for Joseph&#8217;s sustaining of his family during famine (Gen 45:11; 47:12; 50:21) — the parallel establishes Solomon&#8217;s administrative provision as fulfilling the patriarchal type. The rotation system prevented any single district from bearing disproportionate burden — administrative equity was built into the system&#8217;s design.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The provision of barley and straw for horses and swift steeds &#8220;each according to his duty&#8221; documents the logistical system for the cavalry and chariot corps. ANE cavalry logistics required enormous quantities of fodder: a horse requires approximately 5&#8211;6 kg of grain and 10&#8211;12 kg of hay per day; forty thousand horses would require around 200,000&#8211;240,000 kg of grain per day — a consumption level that explains why the district system was structured as it was. The Assyrian military ration documents (Nimrud tablets) confirm comparable fodder requirements for state cavalry forces.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&#8220;God gave Solomon wisdom (<em>ḥokmat</em>) and understanding (<em>tĕbûnāh</em>) beyond measure, and breadth of mind like the sand on the seashore&#8221; — the listing of wisdom, understanding, and &#8220;breadth of mind&#8221; (<em>rōḥab lēb</em>, literally &#8220;width of heart&#8221;) is the characterization of Solomonic intellectual capacity in encyclopedic terms. The sand-of-the-seashore simile (used for the Abrahamic promise of descendants) applies a covenant-blessing image to intellectual capacity: Solomon&#8217;s wisdom is as vast as the promised multitude. This verse opens the summary of Solomon&#8217;s international wisdom reputation (vv. 30&#8211;34) that prepares for the Queen of Sheba narrative (ch10).</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;Solomon&#8217;s wisdom surpassed the wisdom of all the people of the east and all the wisdom of Egypt&#8221; — the &#8220;wisdom of the east&#8221; (<em>ḥokmat kol-bĕnê qedem</em>) refers to the Mesopotamian and Arabian wisdom traditions: the book of Job&#8217;s setting in the east (Uz) and the wise men from the east in Matthew 2 reflect the same ANE understanding of the east as a seat of ancient wisdom. &#8220;All the wisdom of Egypt&#8221; is the other major wisdom tradition: Egypt produced the most extensive wisdom literature of the ancient world (Amenemopet, Ptahhotep, Any, Merikare) — the claim that Solomon exceeded even Egyptian wisdom is a claim to unprecedented universal superiority.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s wisdom exceeded that of specific named sages — Ethan the Ezrahite, Heman, Chalcol, and Darda, &#8220;sons of Mahol.&#8221; Ethan the Ezrahite is identified as the author of Psalm 89; Heman is associated with Psalms 88. These names appear in 1 Chronicles 2:6 as sons of Zerah of Judah — wisdom figures within Israel itself. Chalcol and Darda are otherwise unknown. The naming of comparable sages to be surpassed is a standard rhetorical technique in ANE wisdom literature and royal inscriptions: the king or sage is always measured against and shown to exceed the best-known predecessors. The named sages were apparently well-known in the ancient world as wisdom benchmarks.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Three thousand proverbs (<em>mĕšālîm</em>) and 1,005 songs (<em>šîrîm</em>) attributed to Solomon are the quantitative claims underlying the Solomonic wisdom corpus (Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Song of Solomon in the canon; Wisdom of Solomon in the deuterocanon). ANE wisdom literature was compiled and attributed to royal figures: the Instructions of Amenemhet, the Instruction of Ptahhotep, and the Counsels of Wisdom (attributed to an Assyrian king) follow the same pattern of royal wisdom attribution. The specific numbers (3,000 and 1,005) have the specificity of official archival record rather than literary hyperbole.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s botanical and zoological knowledge — speaking of plants &#8220;from the cedar of Lebanon to the hyssop growing out of the wall&#8221; and of animals, birds, reptiles, and fish — places him in the tradition of ANE scientific encyclopedism. The Egyptian onomastica (&#8220;naming lists&#8221;) like the Onomasticon of Amenemopet (ca. 1100 BCE) organize knowledge of the world by category: sky, water, earth, people, occupations, cities, then an encyclopedic list of plants, animals, birds, fish. The claim that Solomon spoke of all these categories matches the onomasticon genre exactly — Solomon&#8217;s wisdom encompasses systematic knowledge of creation. The range &#8220;from cedar to hyssop&#8221; (the largest to the smallest plant) is a merism indicating comprehensive botanical knowledge.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;People came from all nations to hear the wisdom of Solomon, sent by all the kings of the earth who had heard of his wisdom&#8221; — this is the narrative preparation for the Queen of Sheba&#8217;s visit (1 Kgs 10:1&#8211;13). The international reputation of Solomon&#8217;s wisdom court mirrors the ANE practice of sending envoys to foreign courts to learn wisdom or acquire texts: the Assurbanipal library at Nineveh collected texts from throughout the ancient Near East; the Hittite court received Egyptian literary texts and vice versa. Solomon&#8217;s Jerusalem as an international wisdom center is historically plausible in the context of the 10th century BCE when literacy and international literary exchange were expanding.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>Hiram (Hebrew <em>ḥîrām</em>, Phoenician <em>&#7717;rm</em>) king of Tyre was the son of the Hiram who supplied David with cedar and craftsmen for the palace (2 Sam 5:11) — the relationship thus spanned two generations and two reigns. Tyre was the dominant Phoenician city of the period, controlling the Lebanon cedar trade and the Mediterranean maritime networks. Josephus (Antiquities 8.2.6&#8211;7) claims to have seen records of this correspondence preserved in Tyrian archives, and the Tyrian king-list tradition (preserved in Menander of Ephesus, cited by Josephus) gives Hiram a reign of approximately 34 years contemporary with David and Solomon. The Phoenician alliance was essential: Israel lacked the specialized woodworking and stonecutting skills that Phoenician craftsmen possessed.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s formal message to Hiram initiates the diplomatic exchange that ch5 records. ANE royal correspondence followed strict protocols: the sender identifies himself, addresses the recipient, exchanges health formalities, and states the purpose. The Amarna archive (14th century BCE) and the later Assyrian royal correspondence both illustrate these epistolary conventions. Solomon&#8217;s message is framed as a response to Hiram&#8217;s greeting (v.1) — the reciprocal structure of the exchange reflects peer diplomacy rather than suzerain-vassal communication.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s explanation that David could not build the temple because of &#8220;the wars that surrounded him&#8221; reflects the Deuteronomistic theology of the temple&#8217;s timing: the temple could only be built in a period of rest from enemies (Deut 12:10&#8211;11: &#8220;when he gives you rest from all your enemies around you ... to the place that YHWH your God will choose&#8221;). The 1 Chronicles tradition adds an explicit statement (1 Chr 22:8; 28:3) that David was told he could not build because he was a &#8220;man of blood&#8221; — the Kings narrative is more circumspect, attributing it simply to the ongoing warfare of David&#8217;s reign rather than personal disqualification.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;YHWH my God has given me rest on every side (<em>menûḥāh missābîb</em>)&#8221; is the fulfillment of the Deuteronomic temple-building condition. The term <em>menûḥāh</em> (rest) is the key covenant word: YHWH promises his people rest in the land (Deut 12:9&#8211;10; 25:19); David promises to find a resting place for the ark (Ps 132:8); YHWH promises David rest from all his enemies (2 Sam 7:1,11). Solomon&#8217;s declaration &#8220;there is no adversary (<em>śāṭān</em>) and no misfortune (<em>peganʿ</em> rāʿ)&#8221; identifies the political conditions for temple construction: the absence of external threat and internal crisis. The word <em>śāṭān</em> (adversary/opponent) is the same term used for the divine court&#8217;s adversary figure in Job 1&#8211;2.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&#8220;I intend to build a house for the name of YHWH my God&#8221; — the formulation &#8220;for the name (<em>lĕšēm</em>) of YHWH&#8221; is the Deuteronomic theology of divine dwelling. Deuteronomy 12:5,11,21; 14:23&#8211;24 speak consistently of YHWH &#8220;choosing a place to put his name there&#8221; rather than physically dwelling in the temple. This &#8220;name theology&#8221; is a Deuteronomistic correction of cruder spatial presence ideas: YHWH does not live in the temple; his name (his authority, identity, accessibility) is localized there. The Nathan oracle (2 Sam 7:13) uses exactly this formulation: &#8220;he shall build a house for my name.&#8221;</p>",
    "6": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s request for Lebanese cedar, proposing that his servants work alongside Hiram&#8217;s, and the payment to be determined &#8220;according to all that you say&#8221; — the cedar forests of Lebanon (primarily the <em>&#8219;erez</em>, Cedrus libani) were a Phoenician monopoly throughout the ancient world. The cedars of Lebanon appear in Assyrian annals, Egyptian texts, and Ugaritic literature as the supreme luxury building material. The bark-free, rot-resistant heartwood of mature cedars could reach 30&#8211;40 meters in length — ideal for temple roof beams and door panels. The Phoenician guild of woodcutters (<em>ḥōṭĕbê ʿēṣîm</em>) possessed specialized skills for felling, trimming, and transporting these logs that Israel did not have. Solomon&#8217;s acknowledgment that &#8220;there is no one among us who knows how to cut timber like the Sidonians&#8221; is a frank admission of Phoenician technical superiority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Hiram&#8217;s response &#8220;Blessed be YHWH today who has given David a wise son over this great people&#8221; is the narrator&#8217;s acknowledgment that even a Phoenician king recognizes the divine gift of Solomonic wisdom. Hiram&#8217;s blessing formula is significant: he uses YHWH&#8217;s name, not a Phoenician deity — either the narrator has framed the response theologically, or it reflects the diplomatic courtesy of using the partner&#8217;s deity in correspondence (attested in the Amarna letters where Canaanite vassals occasionally invoke YHWH/El). The political meaning is that the Phoenician-Israelite alliance is presented as having YHWH&#8217;s blessing.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Hiram&#8217;s formal acceptance (&#8220;I will do all you desire in the matter of cedar and cypress timber&#8221;) follows ANE treaty-response conventions: the partner&#8217;s agreement mirrors the proposer&#8217;s request. The inclusion of cypress (<em>bĕrôšîm</em>, probably Cupressus sempervirens) alongside cedar represents the full range of Phoenician prestige timber: cedar for structural beams and panels, cypress for door frames and possibly flooring. Both woods were prized throughout the ancient Near East for their durability and aromatic qualities.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The logistics of timber transport — floated as rafts (<em>dĕbārôt</em>) from Lebanon &#8220;to whatever place you specify&#8221; — reflects the actual practice of Phoenician timber trade. The cedars were felled in the Lebanon mountains, dragged to the coast, tied into log rafts, and floated along the Mediterranean coast to the destination port. From Joppa (the nearest Mediterranean port to Jerusalem, about 55 km from the city), the logs would be hauled overland. The labor involved was enormous: the terrain between Joppa and Jerusalem is hilly, requiring organized teams for the final stage. This logistical chain explains the massive labor force described in vv. 13&#8211;18.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Hiram gave Solomon cedar timber and cypress timber, all that he desired&#8221; — the fulfillment statement after the exchange of terms. The construction of the temple required enormous quantities of timber: 1 Kings 6:15&#8211;18 describes cedar covering of the entire interior — floors, walls, and ceiling — making the temple essentially a cedar-lined chamber. The quantity of cedar used (30 years later Hiram would complain about the inadequacy of Solomon&#8217;s payment, according to Josephus&#8217;s Tyrian sources) suggests a long-running trade relationship that extended well beyond a single building project.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Solomon&#8217;s payment — 20,000 cors of wheat (<em>ḥiṭṭîm</em>, i.e., quality wheat) and 20,000 baths (<em>bat</em>) of fine oil (<em>šemen kātît</em>, beaten/pure olive oil) — reflects the complementary economic specializations of Phoenicia and Israel: Phoenicia provided timber and craftsmanship; Israel provided agricultural surplus (grain, oil, wine). The Phoenician coastal strip was not agriculturally productive — the mountains came close to the sea — so Phoenicia depended on trade with the agricultural hinterland for basic foodstuffs. This exchange is attested in Ezekiel 27:17, which describes Judah and Israel trading wheat, oil, and honey with Tyre. One cor ≈ 220 liters; 20,000 cors of wheat ≈ 4.4 million liters per year — an enormous annual transfer that bound the two economies together.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;YHWH gave Solomon wisdom as he had promised him. And there was peace (<em>šālôm</em>) between Hiram and Solomon, and the two of them made a treaty (<em>bĕrît</em>)&#8221; — the summary verse ties together the wisdom theme (fulfilled promise), the political achievement (peace with Tyre), and the formal status of the relationship (covenant/treaty). The word <em>bĕrît</em> indicates a formal sworn agreement with legal obligations on both sides — not merely a commercial transaction but a binding international treaty. The Assyrian vassal treaties and the Hittite parity treaties both use <em>bĕrît</em>-equivalent terminology for formal international commitments.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;King Solomon drafted forced labor (<em>wayyaʿal hammas</em>) from all Israel — thirty thousand men&#8221; — the corvée labor system (<em>mas</em>) imposed on Israelite citizens is the most consequential administrative decision of Solomon&#8217;s reign for the book&#8217;s narrative arc. The term <em>mas</em> appears earlier in the conquest narratives (Josh 16:10; 17:13; Judg 1:28,30,33,35) for the forced labor imposed on surviving Canaanite populations — Solomon is now imposing the same system on Israelites themselves. The 30,000 men for Lebanon, plus the 70,000 carriers and 80,000 stonecutters of v.15, represents a total conscript labor force of approximately 180,000 men — a massive extraction from an agrarian population of perhaps 2&#8211;3 million. This system is the background grievance that Rehoboam refuses to address in 12:4&#8211;14.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The rotation system — 10,000 men per month in Lebanon, two months at home — was designed to minimize economic disruption to the conscripts&#8217; households. A one-month-in-three rotation allowed men to return to their farms during the two-month rest period, maintaining agricultural productivity. But even with rotation, the conscription represented a substantial extraction of male labor from the agricultural workforce. The overseer Adoniram (v.6 of ch4) managed this logistical system — his name will be cursed by the northern tribes in 12:18. The one-month rotation is attested in Mesopotamian labor documents where state corvée systems used similar rotation schedules.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The additional workforce of 70,000 carriers (<em>nōśĕʾê massāʾ</em>) and 80,000 stonecutters (<em>ḥōṣĕbîm bāhār</em>) — &#8220;in the hill country&#8221; — were employed in the quarrying and transport operations within Canaan itself. The hill country of Judah and Benjamin provided the limestone and other stone for temple foundations and walls (6:36; 7:12). The stonecutters at Gebal (Byblos, v.18) — Phoenician craftsmen — are distinguished from the Israelite stonecutters, indicating specialized guilds for different tasks. The total labor figure (180,000 conscripts plus 3,300 overseers) is comparable to the labor forces documented for Egyptian pyramid construction — the temple was Solomon&#8217;s &#8220;pyramid.&#8221;</p>",
    "16": "<p>The 3,300 supervisors (<em>nĕṣîbîm</em>) who &#8220;oversaw the work&#8221; — the administrative hierarchy for the construction project. The parallel in 2 Chronicles 2:2,18 gives 3,600 supervisors; the discrepancy (300 vs. 600) may reflect different accounting of supervisory categories (local overseers vs. senior managers). The supervisory ratio (approximately 1 overseer per 50 workers) is consistent with what is known from Mesopotamian administrative texts about labor supervision: the Neo-Assyrian records from Assurnasirpal II&#8217;s palace construction (Nimrud, 9th century) document similar supervisory hierarchies for major royal building projects.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The &#8220;large, expensive (<em>yĕqārôt</em>) stones&#8221; — &#8220;dressed stones (<em>ʾabnê gāzît</em>)&#8221; for the foundation — were a specific quarrying achievement. <em>ʾabnê gāzît</em> (ashlar masonry, cut and dressed stone blocks) represents the highest quality of ancient building construction. The temple&#8217;s foundation stones, described in 1 Kings 7:10 as &#8220;great stones, stones of eight cubits and stones of ten cubits&#8221; (4&#8211;5 meters in length), are comparable to the massive ashlar stones found at Megiddo and Gezer from the Solomonic period. Quarrying, shaping, and transporting stones of this size required sophisticated infrastructure: sledges, wooden rollers, ramps, and large organized teams.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;Solomon&#8217;s builders and Hiram&#8217;s builders and the men of Gebal (<em>giblîm</em>) cut and prepared the timber and the stone&#8221; — the men of Gebal (Byblos, modern Jbeil, Lebanon) were Phoenician craftsmen famous throughout the ancient world for their masonry and carpentry. The term &#8220;Giblite&#8221; (<em>giblî</em>) appears in Ezekiel 27:9 as skilled ship repairers — Byblos was famous for its craftsmen and its papyrus trade (&#8220;byblos&#8221; = papyrus = &#8220;Bible&#8221;). The joint Israeli-Phoenician labor force for the temple construction represents a remarkable international collaborative enterprise — the house of YHWH was built with the labor and skills of both covenant people and pagan craftsmen, the same dynamic that will appear in the NT where the church is built from both Jewish and Gentile materials.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('context', '1kings')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('context', '1kings', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'1kings mkt-context: wrote {total} verses across ch 3-5')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
